<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Congress specifically limited field citations to minor 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
violations, as defined by the Agency. While EPA's proposed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
definition of minor violation does not specify each and every 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
violation that might be considered minor, it does set clear 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
limits on the kinds of violations that will be considered minor 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
violations. The many different kinds of violations that may meet 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the definition of minor violation will exhibit common features. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
For example, the typical minor violation will involve a clear and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
straightforward violation, both factually and legally, of limited 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
frequency or duration and limited environmental impact. The 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
factual and legal issues that EPA expects to arise in field 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
citation assessments are, overall, expected to be simple and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
uncomplicated. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The basic private interest at stake is the assessment of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
civil penalties of up to a maximum of $5,000 per day for each 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
violation, as well as the resources needed to contest such 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
assessments where considered appropriate. The maximum penalty is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
significantly lower than the maximum administrative or judicial 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
civil penalties authorized under sections 113, 205 and 211 of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The primary governmental interest is implementation of a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
program that fairly fills a gap in EPA's enforcement programs, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
without undue drain on EPA's limited enforcement resources. EPA 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
believes this interest is best served by addressing minor 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
violations in a straightforward and direct manner, somewhat akin 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to a traffic enforcement program. The deterrence effect from 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
this program will come in large part from the issuance of a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
citation immediately upon or shortly after detection of a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
violation, with final assessment of the penalty occurring shortly 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
after issuance of the citation. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
EPA has considered these and other factors in evaluating the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
three options proposed today for hearing procedures, and believes 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
all three fully implement Congressional intent and satisfy due 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
process requirements. The three options draw different balances 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
between complexity and simplicity, formality and informality, but 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
are all designed to implement a program aimed at simple and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
uncomplicated violations, involving penalties significantly lower 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
than others authorized in the Act, and requiring straightforward, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
quick and fair adjudication to obtain the desired deterrent 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
effect without undue drain on limited Agency resources. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=1 -->
1. Modified 40 CFR Part 22_Consolidated Rules of Practice 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Governing the Administrative Assessment of Civil Penalties 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and the Revocation or Suspension of Permits 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Under the first Agency proposal, administrative hearings on 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
field citations would be conducted pursuant to the procedures 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
established by EPA
<!-- PJG 0034 unknown -->
s consolidated APA rules of practice for the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
administrative assessment of civil penalties, 40 CFR part 22. In 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
a separate rulemaking, the Agency would propose to amend part 22, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
where appropriate, to make that regulation applicable to field 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
citations. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

