<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
At the hearing, the Agency has the burden of going forward 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and proving that the violation occurred and that the proposed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
penalty is appropriate. After a prima facie case is established, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the Respondent has the burden of presenting and going forward 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
with any defense to the allegations in the citation. The matters 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in controversy are determined by the Presiding Officer upon a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
preponderance of evidence. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The hearing must be transcribed. Within twenty days after 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the transcript is available, the parties may submit proposed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
findings of fact and conclusions of law with supporting briefs. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Reply briefs are also authorized. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The Presiding Officer issues the initial decision, which 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
consists of findings of fact, conclusions of law, and recommended 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
civil penalty. In reaching an initial decision, the Presiding 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Officer is required to consider the statutory penalty assessment 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
criteria listed in section 113(e), section 205(c) or section 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
211(d) of the Act, as appropriate. For section 113(e), these 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
criteria include: The size of the business; the economic impact 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of the penalty on the business; the Respondent's full compliance 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
history; the Respondent's good faith efforts to comply; the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
duration of the violation as established by any credible 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
evidence; payment by the Respondent of penalties previously 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
assessed for the same violation; the economic benefit of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
noncompliance; the seriousness of the violation; and such other 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
factors as justice may require. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
If the Presiding Officer recommends a penalty different from 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the one proposed by the citation, the initial decision must set 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
forth the specific reasons for the increase or decrease. Either 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
party may file a motion to reopen the hearing within twenty (20) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
days of service of the initial decision. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Unless a party appeals to the Environmental Appeals Board 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(the Board) within twenty (20) days of service, or unless the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Board elects to review it 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
sua sponte
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
, the Presiding Officer's 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
initial decision becomes a final order of the Board within forty-five (45) days after service. A final order of the
Board shall 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
adopt, modify or set aside the findings and conclusions of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
initial decision. The Board is authorized to increase or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
decrease the assessed penalty, except in the case of a default 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
order. A motion for reconsideration of the final order may be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
filed with the Board within ten (10) days after service of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
final order. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
Procedural Due Process 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
EPA analyzed the issue of procedural due process with its 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
consolidated APA rules of practice when they were promulgated. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
See 52 FR 2922 (August 6, 1987) (NPRM) and 57 FR 4316 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(February 4, 1992) (FRM). In that analysis EPA evaluated and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
balanced the three factors specified by the Supreme Court in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Mathews 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
v. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Eldridge
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
, 424 U.S. 319 (1976) for determining whether 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the administrative procedure provided to an individual prior to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the deprivation of a property interest meets the due process 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requirements of the Fifth Amendment: the magnitude and nature of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the individual interest at stake, the risk of an erroneous 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
deprivation of that interest and the benefit of additional 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
procedures in reducing that risk, and the governmental interest 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in not providing such additional procedures. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
EPA's APA style hearing procedures would certainly satisfy 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
procedural due process considerations as well as statutory 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
requirements if employed for hearings on field citations. By 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
statute APA adjudication procedures are not required. The 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
violations are by definition minor in nature and should involve 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
simple and straightforward factual and legal situations. In 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
fact, EPA believes these procedures provide significantly more 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
process than required by the Fifth Amendment for hearings on 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
field citations, and are proposed as an option not because of due 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
process considerations but because of the expected benefits of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
having a single set of procedures governing all administrative 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
penalty proceedings under the Clean Air Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
EPA is also considering certain revisions to the Part 22 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
procedures to account for the minor nature of the violations at 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
issue under the field citation program. First, EPA is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
considering using presiding officers that are not administrative 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
law judges. As with other non-APA situations, the agency's 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
presiding officers would conduct the hearings and take other 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
actions. This would help to conserve the agency's administrative 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
law judge resources for APA hearings, with no expected reduction 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in the accuracy of the hearing process. The Agency is also 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
considering such revisions as making the prehearing conference 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
optional and changing the deadline for default from twenty to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
thirty days following service. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
